english:
  title: Zheng Hui
  author: Lee Inbok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Upon the trellis, grapevines grow thick and full,
    While weeds in the garden grow sparse and rare.
    Roots taking hold now begin to flourish,
    Tendrils stretching forth, leaning upon each other.

    Like dragons and serpents they race and writhe,
    Nourished fat by the grace of rain and dew.
    They cover the steps, heavy with abundance,
    Spread round the house, reaching toward every corner.

    Unfurled to the side like azure silk quilts,
    Hanging across like strands of jade thread.
    Blue mist hovers above the courtyard,
    Colored clouds flicker swift against the windows.

    Fine fruit ripens when autumn comes,
    Yet bitter winds may scatter the leaves.
    The taste, exquisite and rare beyond measure—
    The wine made from them holds no weakness either.

    I ask you then: though governing brings its joys,
    How could it compare to one night of gentle inebriation?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem uses the grapevine as a metaphor for flourishing governance and prosperity within a region or household.
  - key: ''
    value: The final couplet presents a philosophical question comparing the satisfaction of administrative duties with the simple pleasure of wine and rest.
